          "body": "The opening parable (18:1-8) frames the chapter not as ethics but as eschatology. Jesus 'was telling them a parable to show that at all times they ought to pray and not to lose heart' — the very first clause names persistent prayer as the topic. Then comes the *qal vahomer* (lesser-to-greater) argument: if even an unjust judge yields to a persistent widow, *how much more* will the righteous God bring about justice for His elect who cry day and night? But the parable ends on a sober note (v.8b): *when the Son of Man comes, will He find faith on the earth?* The faith Jesus looks for at His return is not generic belief — it is the specific faith that *keeps praying* through long delay. Persistent prayer is the marker of saving faith in the chapter's logic."
